    <maml:alertSet>
      <maml:alert>
        <maml:para>The `PIZZA_CONTENTS` argument can also be explicitly set using `-Contents PIZZA_CONTENTS`, to follow common PowerShell cmdlet conventions. If multiple parts of pizza contents are defined, the program only selects the first string detected after the first invocation of `-Contents`.</maml:para>
        <maml:para>Even though the DOS, POSIX, and PowerShell variants of this programs are made available for many operating systems and shell environments, some advanced command-line features might not be consistent between them.</maml:para>
        <maml:para>For example, you want to call PowerShell-based `New-Pizza -Pineapple $false -Name "Great Pizza"` in Bash. But in Bash, `$false` will instead recall the value of the shell session variable `false`.</maml:para>
        <maml:para>Since `false` is clearly unset, Bash will return `$false` as null (or no value), and `New-Pizza` will instead receive your command as `New-Pizza -Pineapple -Name "Great Pizza"`, which means the pineapple will still be added to your pizza. Oh, no!</maml:para>
        <maml:para>&gt; To solve this issue in POSIX-based shells: use escape characters ``, so the command becomes `New-Pizza -Pineapple \$false -Name "Great Pizza"`</maml:para>
        <maml:para>`mkpizza`, `makepizza`, and `New-Pizza` will try to interpret the remaining command-line input as literal strings, so they won't be able to parse advanced shell data structures like lists/arrays, and PowerShell's `HashTable`s. Many shell environments allow you to execute shell subcommands and carry their results to the final `makepizza` command, but the uniqueness or differences between these shells are out of the scope of this software.</maml:para>
      </maml:alert>
    </maml:alertSet>
    <command:examples>
      <command:example>
        <maml:title>-------------- Example 1: Create Johny, the Pizza --------------</maml:title>
        <dev:code>New-Pizza -Name Johny "Johny, the Pizza"</dev:code>
        <dev:remarks>
          <maml:para>This command creates a new pizza named Johny, using the `-Name` parameter.</maml:para>
        </dev:remarks>
      </command:example>
      <command:example>
        <maml:title>-------- Example 2: You forgor to remove the pineapple --------</maml:title>
        <dev:code>New-Pizza -Name Johny -Pineapple $false "Johny, the Pizza"</dev:code>
        <dev:remarks>
          <maml:para>Apparently, this program has the algorithmic affinity to put pineapples on pizza.</maml:para>
          <maml:para>Oh, yuck! Make another one without it.</maml:para>
        </dev:remarks>
      </command:example>
      <command:example>
        <maml:title>------------- Example 3: Cook it a little bit more -------------</maml:title>
        <dev:code>New-Pizza -Name Johny -Pineapple $false -Duration 67 "Johny, the Pizza"</dev:code>
        <dev:remarks>
          <maml:para>Nice! You'd think cooking the pizza longer could mean better, crispier piece of bread!</maml:para>
          <maml:para>Try to cook for 67 seconds while you put the fries in the bag.</maml:para>
        </dev:remarks>
      </command:example>
      <command:example>
        <maml:title>------------------ Example 4: root vibes only ------------------</maml:title>
        <dev:code>New-Pizza -Name Johny -Pineapple $false -Duration 67 -CheckSuperuser -ExitCode 165 "Johny, the Pizza"</dev:code>
        <dev:remarks>
          <maml:para>You'd think cooking a pizza for 67 seconds is insecure by default. Skibidi people could have tried to poison your pizza.</maml:para>
          <maml:para>Therefore, to maintain supply-chain security, only allow `root`, `sudoer`, or Administrator users to make the pizza. And just to be secure, please return an exit code of `165` instead of `0`.</maml:para>
        </dev:remarks>
      </command:example>
    </command:examples>
